Two circles have the same center O. Point X is the midpoint of segment OP. What is the ratio of the area of the circle with radius OX to the area of the circle with radius OP? Express your answer as a common fraction.

[asy]
import graph;
draw(Circle((0,0),20));
draw(Circle((0,0),12));
dot((0,0));
dot((20,0));
dot((12,0));
draw((0,0)--(20,0));
label("$O$",(0,0),SE);
label("$P$",(20,0),E);
label("$X$",(12,0),SE);
[/asy] The area of a circle is proportional to the square of its radius.
Let $r$ be the radius of the circle with radius OX, and let $R$ be the radius of the circle with radius OP.
Then the area of the circle with radius OX is $\pi r^2$, and the area of the circle with radius OP is $\pi R^2$.
Since X is the midpoint of segment OP, we have $r=\frac{R}{2}$.
